</p>
<h3>
    Effective Baits and Lures
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spinners:</strong> Panther Martin, Rooster Tail (1/16 oz)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Natural Baits:</strong> Worms, salmon eggs
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Flies:</strong> Elk hair caddis, beadhead nymphs, and soft hackles
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Fly Fishing Setup for Cutthroat
</h3>
<p>
    Use a floating line with 9-foot 4X leader. Dry-dropper rigs work well, especially during mid-morning hatches. Be sure to match your fly to seasonal insect activity.
</p>
<h2>
    Techniques for Catching Cutthroat Trout
</h2>
<h3>
    Spin Fishing Strategies
</h3>
<p>
    Cast upstream and retrieve slowly through likely holding areas—riffles, pools, and eddies. Use light line (4-6 lb test) for a more natural presentation.
</p>
<h3>
    Fly Fishing Techniques
</h3>
<p>
    Cutthroat are eager risers. Try dead-drifting dry flies or swinging soft hackles across runs. Terrestrial patterns (like ants and hoppers) work great during summer.
</p>
<h3>
    Shore vs Boat Fishing
</h3>
<p>
    Shore fishing is widely accessible near Eugene. However, a <strong>drift boat on the McKenzie</strong> can offer access to untouched runs and remote pools. Just be aware of fast currents and always wear a PFD.
